Ever since our primary school math classes, we have all been taught one absolute rule: "A number cannot be divided by zero; it is undefined."
Imagine you are holding 10 apples in your hands. I ask you to distribute them equally among 0 people. How many apples does each person get? 
You can't answer that. You can't give apples to people who don't exist. The logic completely breaks down. The physical act of dividing something 
into "zero groups" is impossible.

C# stays entirely loyal to this mathematical rule. If you try to force the computer to divide a number by zero during runtime, the processor realizes 
it cannot calculate the impossible. It immediately halts the program's flow, effectively shouting, "I cannot do this!" and throws a DivideByZeroException.

## The Technical Reality

At the hardware level, dividing an integer by zero triggers a fault directly in the CPU. The .NET runtime catches this hardware-level panic and wraps 
it into a neat DivideByZeroException object for you to handle. If you do not handle it, your application will crash instantly.

## Let's Look at the Code

// SCENARIO 1: Integers (The exact moment the application crashes)
int appleCount = 10;
int personCount = 0;

// BOOM! The program explodes right here.
// The CPU refuses to calculate 10 / 0, so a DivideByZeroException is thrown!
int applesPerPerson = appleCount / personCount;
